HIV/AIDS: China reported a 14% increase in new cases
China has reported a 14% jump in the number of new cases of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people in the country have been affected, health officials say.
About 40,000 new cases were recorded only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases have been transmitted through sexual intercourse, which is a change from the previous state of affairs.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly to some parts of China as a result of blood transfusions infected with the virus.
However, the number of people who receive HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, from year to year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 people.
HIV transmission through sexual relations is a pressing problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has no longer been considered illegal in China since 1997, but they say discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
Studies estimate that, due to conservative understandings in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with men eventually marry women.
The transmission of the virus often occurs due to inappropriate sexual protection in such relationships.
In 2003, the Chinese government promised universal access to HIV drugs as part of a plan to solve this problem.
