Latest news about the flowering of the sea: concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Mantee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Commission on the conservation of fish and natural habitat of Florida shows a general decline in the concentration of seafloor in parts of the Tampa Bay.
According to FWC, sporadic flowering has been reported in areas of Pinellas, Mentee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - which indicates a decrease in concentration.
The surface of the flowering sea extends to about 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to Lee County in the south.
The booming surfaces appear about 10 miles from the shores of Hillsborough County, but in smaller places compared to last week.
The flowering of the sea is also recorded in the district of Pasco.
In the past week, middle concentrations have been recorded in Pinellas County, low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, average to high concentrations in Manatee County, average to high concentrations in Sarasota County or its coastline, average to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, average to high concentrations in Lee County or its coastline, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Cases of airway irritation continue to occur in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no cases of airway irritations in northwestern Florida over the past week.
